s the ancient understanding of smell through religious rituals, liturgical practices, mystagogical commentaries, literary imagery, homiletic conventions; scientific, medical, and cosmological models; ascetic disciplines, theological discourse, and eschatological expectations. In the process, she argues for a richer appreciation of ancient notions of embodiment, and of the roles the body might serve in religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aOdors. 0aSacrifice. 0aSenses and sensationxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aSmellxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aWorship. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aaffect theory.  aasceticism.  abodily senses.  abody.  aceremony.  achristianity.  achurch history.  acosmology.  adevotionals.  adivine order.  adivinity.  adoctrine.  aearly christianity.  aembodiment.  aeschatology.  ahistory.  aholy oils.  ahomily.  aincense.  aliturgy.  amediterranean culture.  amediterranean.  amystagogy.  anonfiction.  aolfactory.  apiety.  areligion and science.  areligious practice.  areligious studies.  arevelation.  arite.  aritual.  asacred scents.  asacred.  ascents.  asensation.  asense of smell.  asensibilia.  asensory experience.  asmell.  aspirituality.  atheology.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093101540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931015/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles